A [remote control](/Remote_control), colloquially known to the less discerning as merely a "remote" or, with a particularly quaint nostalgia, a "clicker," [^1] is an [electronic device](/Consumer_electronics) whose fundamental purpose is to operate another, more significant device from a respectable distance. This operation is typically achieved [wirelessly](/Wireless), a testament to humanity’s enduring desire to exert influence without expending undue physical effort. In the sprawling domain of [consumer electronics](/Consumer_electronics), these ubiquitous little rectangles are employed to command an array of appliances, from the venerable [television set](/Television_set) to the ever-present [DVD player](/DVD_player) or any other digital home media apparatus that demands your attention, yet not your proximity.

A remote control fundamentally offers the convenience of operating devices that are inconveniently beyond direct reach. They function with optimal efficiency when deployed from a relatively short distance, a limitation that hardly deters their widespread adoption. While primarily a feature born of user comfort, in more pragmatic scenarios, remote controls empower individuals to operate devices that would otherwise be utterly inaccessible. Consider, for instance, the [garage door opener](/Garage_door_opener), which can be triggered from the comfortable confines of a vehicle, sparing one the indignity of physical exertion in inclement weather.

The widely recognized symbol indicating the use of [infrared](/Infrared_communication) technology for signal transmission to devices is a common sight, a silent acknowledgment of the predominant communication method.

Historically, the earliest iterations of television remote controls, prevalent between 1956 and 1977, relied on the rather quaint method of [ultrasonic](/Ultrasonics) tones. However, the vast majority of present-day remote controls have evolved into [consumer infrared](/Consumer_IR) devices. These sophisticated (or, at least, sufficiently functional) gadgets transmit digitally coded pulses of infrared radiation, a silent language of light that orchestrates a symphony of functions: power toggling, volume adjustment, channel navigation, media playback control, track skipping, energy management, fan speed regulation, and a myriad of other specialized features. The physical manifestation of these remote controls is typically a small, handheld, [wireless](/Wireless) object, adorned with an array of buttons, each patiently awaiting its moment of utility. They are the instruments by which one fine-tunes the digital landscape, adjusting everything from the current [television channel](/Television_channel) to the track number on a media player, or the universally understood metric of [volume](/Loudness). It is a tiresome truth that the specific remote control code, and consequently, the precisely required remote control device, is usually proprietary to a particular product line. Thankfully, the market, ever eager to capitalize on our collective exasperation, offers [universal remotes](/Universal_remote), which possess the admirable (or perhaps just expected) ability to emulate the control signals of most major brand devices, offering a small reprieve from the tyranny of multiple controllers.

As the 21st century progressed, remote controls embraced newer technologies. Those emerging in the 2000s began to incorporate [Bluetooth](/Bluetooth) or [Wi-Fi](/Wi-Fi) connectivity, transcending the line-of-sight limitations of infrared. They also introduced [motion sensor](/Motion_sensor)-enabled capabilities, allowing for more intuitive, if occasionally flailing, interactions, and even [voice control](/Voice_control), catering to those who prefer to command their devices with spoken words rather than mere button presses. [^2] [^3] Remote controls designed for [Smart TVs](/Smart_TV) from the 2010s onward have further diversified their functionality, often featuring a complete, standalone keyboard on their reverse side to streamline the arduous process of typing, and frequently doubling as a pointing device, allowing for cursor-based navigation of the increasingly complex on-screen interfaces. [^4] It seems the only thing they won't do is make you a sandwich.

## History

*   Further information: [Radio control § History](/Radio_control)

The very concept of [wired](/Wire) and [wireless remote control](/Wireless) began to materialize in the latter half of the 19th century, driven by a rather specific and, dare I say, predictable human need: the control of unmanned vehicles. These were, for the most part, military [torpedoes](/Torpedoes), because what else would we prioritize controlling remotely? This early period saw the emergence of a wired variant in 1870, courtesy of the German engineer [Werner von Siemens](/Werner_von_Siemens). Not long after, the British engineers Ernest Wilson and C. J. Evans introduced radio-controlled versions in 1897. [^6] [^7] Perhaps the most celebrated early demonstration was a prototype unveiled by the visionary inventor [Nikola Tesla](/Nikola_Tesla) in New York in 1898, showcasing a radio-controlled boat, a marvel of its time. [^8]

In 1903, the Spanish engineer [Leonardo Torres Quevedo](/Leonardo_Torres_Quevedo) presented his groundbreaking radio-based control system, which he christened the " [Telekino](/Telekino) ," at the esteemed [Paris Academy of Sciences](/Paris_Academy_of_Sciences). [^9] His ambition was to utilize this system to control a [dirigible airship](/Astra-Torres_airship) of his own ingenious design. What set the Telekino apart from its rudimentary "on/off" predecessors was its remarkable capacity to execute a finite, yet considerably varied, set of distinct mechanical actions through the use of a single [communication channel](/Communication_channel). [^10] [^11] From 1904 to 1906, Torres Quevedo meticulously conducted testings of his Telekino system. These trials involved a [three-wheeled land vehicle](/Tricycle) that demonstrated an effective control range of 20 to 30 meters, and, more impressively, the remote guidance of a manned, electrically powered [boat](/Boat), which showcased a standoff range extending up to 2 kilometers. [^12] The advent of the first remote-controlled model airplane, taking to the skies in 1932, [^citation needed] further solidified the potential of this technology. The pressing demands of the [Second World War](/Second_World_War) spurred intensive development of remote control technology for military applications, leading to advanced systems such as the German [Wasserfall missile](/Wasserfall_missile), a grim testament to human ingenuity applied to destruction.

### Philco Mystery Control (1939)

By the late 1930s, a handful of forward-thinking radio manufacturers began to offer remote controls, albeit typically for their more exclusive, higher-end models. [^13] The majority of these early consumer remote controls were tethered to the device they commanded by an unseemly tangle of wires, a physical limitation that rather undermined the "remote" aspect. However, the [Philco](/Philco) Mystery Control, introduced in 1939, bravely broke from this convention. It operated as a battery-powered, low-frequency radio transmitter, [^14] thereby earning its place in history as the very first wireless remote control specifically designed for a [consumer electronics](/Consumer_electronics) device. Furthermore, by employing pulse-count modulation, this device also holds the distinction of being the inaugural digital wireless remote control, a surprisingly early foray into digital communication for the common household.

## Television remote controls

### Early Innovations (1950s)

One of the earliest devices conceived with the sole purpose of controlling a [television](/Television) from a distance was brought forth by the [Zenith Radio Corporation](/Zenith_Electronics_Corporation) in 1950. This pioneering remote, rather aptly named "Lazy Bones," [^15] was, however, still physically linked to the television by a wire. A small step for man, a slightly larger step for those who preferred not to stand.

The true leap into wireless control for televisions arrived in 1955 with the development of the [Flash-Matic](/Zenith_Flash-matic) by [Eugene Polley](/Eugene_Polley). [^15] [^16] This ingenious, if somewhat flawed, device functioned by emitting a beam of light, which was then directed at one of four [photoelectric cells](/Solar_cell) strategically placed on the television. [^17] Unfortunately, the sophistication of these cells was limited; they proved utterly incapable of distinguishing between the light emanating from the remote itself and light from any other ambient source, leading to accidental channel changes from sunlight or lamps. [^18] Adding to its charming quirks, the Flash-Matic also demanded an almost surgical precision in aiming, requiring the user to point it very accurately at one of the tiny sensors for it to register a command. [^18] [^19] A truly engaging user experience, I'm sure.

### The Zenith Space Commander (1956)

A year later, in 1956, [Robert Adler](/Robert_Adler) introduced what many consider the first truly practical wireless television remote control: the Zenith Space Command. [^15] [^20] [^21] This marvel of mid-century engineering was entirely mechanical in its operation and ingeniously utilized [ultrasound](/Ultrasonics) to manipulate both the channel and the volume. [^22] [^21] When a user, in a moment of inspired indolence, pressed a button on this remote, it would physically strike a small bar, producing an audible "click." This distinctive sound earned these devices the affectionate, if slightly dismissive, moniker of "clickers." The internal mechanics were surprisingly akin to a [plectrum](/Plectrum) striking a guitar string, albeit for less melodious purposes. [^21] [^23] Each of the four bars within the remote was meticulously tuned to emit a different fundamental frequency, accompanied by specific ultrasonic harmonics. Circuits embedded within the television were then designed to detect these unique acoustic signatures, interpreting them as distinct commands: channel-up, channel-down, sound-on/off, and power-on/off. [^24]

### Evolution to Electronic and Digital Control

As technology relentlessly marched forward, the rapid and significant decrease in the manufacturing cost of [transistors](/Transistor) paved the way for the creation of far cheaper, entirely [electronic](/Electronics) remotes. These newer devices often contained a [piezoelectric](/Piezoelectricity) crystal, which was energized by an [oscillating](/Oscillation) electric current at a [frequency](/Frequency) that hovered near or even above the upper threshold of [human hearing](/Hearing_(sense)). While largely inaudible to most adults, these frequencies were, to the mild annoyance of pet owners, still within the range of detection for [dogs](/Dog). The corresponding receiver within the television housed a [microphone](/Microphone) linked to a circuit precisely tuned to the same frequency. This method, while an improvement, was not without its own set of charming drawbacks. The receiver could be inadvertently triggered by naturally occurring noises, or, more mischievously, by deliberate sounds like metal scraping against glass. And, of course, some particularly sensitive individuals *could* indeed perceive the lower ultrasonic harmonics, adding an unwelcome auditory dimension to their channel surfing.

A significant leap forward arrived in 1970 when [RCA](/RCA_Corporation) unveiled an entirely electronic remote control system. This innovation embraced the nascent power of [digital signals](/Digital_signal) and integrated [metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor](/Metal%E2%80%93oxide%E2%80%93semiconductor_field-effect_transistor) (MOSFET) [memory](/Semiconductor_memory) technology. This development proved to be a pivotal moment, leading to its widespread adoption, particularly for [color television](/Color_television) sets, and effectively rendering the older, motor-driven tuning controls obsolete. [^25]

The true impetus for the development of a more sophisticated and complex type of television remote control emerged in 1973, with the launch of the [Ceefax](/Ceefax) [teletext](/Teletext) service by the venerable [BBC](/BBC). At this juncture, most commercial remote controls were rather limited in their functional repertoire, sometimes offering as few as three basic commands: next channel, previous channel, and a combined volume/off function. This minimalist approach was woefully inadequate for the demands of Teletext sets, where pages were identified by three-digit numbers, requiring direct numerical input. Consequently, a remote control capable of selecting Teletext pages would necessitate individual buttons for each numeral from zero to nine, alongside various other control functions such as toggling between text and picture modes, in addition to the standard television controls for volume, channel, brightness, and color intensity. Early Teletext sets initially relied on wired remote controls for page selection, but the continuous and often rapid use demanded by Teletext quickly underscored the urgent need for a wireless solution. This realization prompted engineers at the BBC to engage in discussions with several television manufacturers, culminating in the creation of early prototypes around 1977–1978. These pioneering devices were capable of controlling a significantly expanded range of functions. [ITT](/ITT_Corporation) was one of the key companies involved in this evolutionary process, and their contributions were later immortalized in the ITT protocol of infrared communication. [^26]

## TV, VHS and DVD Remote controls

The 1980s heralded a new era of remote control prominence. In 1980, one of the most widely adopted remote controls was the Starcom Cable TV Converter, a product of [Jerrold Electronics](/Jerrold_Electronics), a division of [General Instrument](/General_Instrument). [^15] [^failed verification] This device, clinging to the fading glory of older technologies, still employed 40-kHz sound to change channels.

However, a Canadian company, Viewstar, Inc., founded by the engineer Paul Hrivnak, soon entered the fray, ushering in the modern era. Viewstar began manufacturing a [cable TV converter](/Cable_converter_box) that, crucially, featured an [infrared](/Infrared_communication) remote control. This innovative product was distributed through Philips and retailed for approximately $190 [CAD](/Canadian_dollar). The Viewstar converter proved to be an immediate and resounding success, achieving the milestone of its millionth unit sold by March 21, 1985, and by 1989, a staggering 1.6 million units had found their way into homes. [^27] [^28] This marked a clear shift in consumer preference towards the more streamlined and silent infrared technology.

## Other remote controls

Beyond the realm of television and media players, the remote control found its way into other ingenious, and sometimes slightly absurd, applications.

The "Blab-off," a rather pointedly named wired remote control, emerged in 1952. Its singular, glorious purpose was to provide viewers with the ability to instantly mute their television's audio, thereby allowing them to mercifully escape the relentless onslaught of commercials. [^29] A valiant, if ultimately futile, rebellion against the inevitable.

In the 1980s, [Steve Wozniak](/Steve_Wozniak), the co-founder of [Apple](/Apple_Inc.), embarked on a new venture by establishing a company named [CL 9](/CL_9). The ambitious goal of this enterprise was to engineer a single remote control capable of operating multiple disparate electronic devices, a noble quest for order in the growing chaos of consumer electronics. The fruits of their labor, the CORE unit (Controller Of Remote Equipment), was unveiled in the autumn of 1987. The CORE unit's significant advantage lay in its remarkable ability to "learn" and store remote signals from a vast array of different devices. Furthermore, it possessed the capacity to execute specific or even multiple functions at predetermined times, thanks to its integrated clock. It also holds the distinction of being the first remote control that could be seamlessly linked to a computer, allowing for the loading of updated software code as needed, a truly forward-thinking feature. Despite its innovative capabilities, the CORE unit never achieved a substantial impact on the mass market. Its complexity and the demanding programming process proved far too cumbersome for the average user, though it did garner enthusiastic reviews from the technically inclined who managed to master its intricacies. [^citation needed] These market obstacles ultimately led to the demise of CL 9, but two of its former employees, undeterred, continued the business under the new name Celadon, carrying forward the legacy of one of the first truly computer-controlled learning remote controls to grace the market. [^30]

By the 1990s, the automotive industry, ever keen on convenience, increasingly integrated electronic remote control door locks into new cars. These remotes transmit a secure signal to the vehicle, enabling the owner to effortlessly lock or unlock the car doors, or even release the trunk, with a simple button press. A popular aftermarket device, particularly prevalent in countries with harsh winter climates, is the remote starter. This allows a car owner to remotely start their vehicle, a feature especially cherished by those who wish to warm up the car and activate the heater and defrost systems for several minutes before venturing out, thereby clearing ice and snow from the windows without having to brave the frigid outdoors. A small luxury, perhaps, but one that speaks volumes about our aversion to discomfort.

## Proliferation

By the dawn of the 21st century, the sheer number of [consumer electronic devices](/Consumer_electronics) populating the average home had swelled dramatically, leading to a corresponding and often overwhelming increase in the number of remote controls required to manage them all. According to the [Consumer Electronics Association](/Consumer_Electronics_Association), the typical American household, in a display of admirable consumerism, possessed an average of four remotes. [^citation needed] For those ambitious enough to assemble a full [home theater](/Home_cinema) system, the situation escalated rapidly, often demanding the orchestration of as many as five or six distinct remotes. This digital orchestra typically included separate controllers for the cable or satellite receiver, the [VCR](/VCR) or [digital video recorder](/Digital_video_recorder) (DVR/PVR), the [DVD player](/DVD_player), the [TV](/Television) itself, and the [audio amplifier](/Audio_amplifier). The particularly frustrating aspect was that several of these remotes often needed to be used in a precise, sequential manner for certain programs or services to function correctly, transforming a simple act of entertainment into a convoluted ritual. This growing cumbersome nature was exacerbated by the unfortunate absence of universally accepted interface guidelines, leaving users to decipher each manufacturer's unique logic.

One pragmatic solution devised to mitigate this relentless proliferation of remotes was the advent of the [universal remote](/Universal_remote). These clever devices are pre-programmed with the operational codes for the majority of major brands of televisions, DVD players, and other home electronics, offering a consolidated command center. In the early 2010s, many [smartphone](/Smartphone) manufacturers, recognizing a lucrative opportunity to further embed themselves into our daily lives, began to incorporate [infrared](/Infrared_communication) emitters directly into their devices. This ingenious integration effectively transformed smartphones into highly versatile universal remotes, accessible via an included or easily downloadable [app](/Mobile_app). [^31] Because, clearly, what we needed was one more device to control all the others.

## Technique

The dominant technological paradigm underpinning the vast majority of home remote controls is the judicious application of [infrared](/Infrared_communication) (IR) light. The signal, a silent ballet between a remote control handset and the device it intends to command, consists of meticulously timed pulses of infrared light. This light, mercifully, remains entirely invisible to the limited spectrum of the [human eye](/Human_eye), yet, with a touch of modern magic, can be readily observed through the lenses of a digital camera, video camera, or even the ubiquitous phone camera.

The transmitter, typically a humble [light-emitting diode](/Light-emitting_diode) (LED) discreetly nestled within the pointing end of the remote control handset, springs into action when a user presses one of its myriad buttons. It then dutifully sends forth a precise stream of infrared light pulses. Each button press is encoded into a unique pattern of these pulses, a digital fingerprint of intent. The receiver, patiently awaiting its cues within the target device, meticulously recognizes this specific pattern and, in turn, orchestrates the device to respond accordingly, fulfilling the user's silent command. [^32]

### Opto components and circuits

The emission spectrum of a typical remote control, such as one used for a sound system, falls squarely within the near [infrared](/Infrared) range. The heart of this system is an infrared [diode](/LED) which modulates its output at a speed precisely corresponding to a particular function. When observed through the lens of a digital camera, this diode appears to be emitting rapid pulses of a distinct purple light, revealing its invisible labor.

For remote controls designed for electronic appliances, a near [infrared](/Infrared) [diode](/LED) is the standard emitter, projecting a focused beam of light towards the target device. A common and effective wavelength for this infrared light is 940 [nanometres](/Nanometre) (nm). [^33] As previously noted, this infrared light is imperceptible to the [human eye](/Human_eye), yet it is readily detected by the specialized sensors embedded within the receiving device. Curiously, video cameras are capable of rendering the output of this diode as if it were producing visible purple light.

In the case of a single-channel (meaning single-function, one-button) remote control, the mere presence of a [carrier signal](/Carrier_signal) is sufficient to trigger a designated function. However, for the more prevalent multi-channel (i.e., normal multi-function) remote controls, a more sophisticated set of procedures becomes absolutely necessary. One common approach involves modulating the carrier signal with distinct signals of varying frequencies. Once the receiver has dutifully demodulated the incoming signal, it then applies the appropriate frequency filters to meticulously separate and identify the respective commands. A curious side effect, often audible to the keen ear, is that one can frequently detect the signals being modulated on the infrared carrier by operating a remote control in very close proximity to an [AM radio](/AM_radio) that is not currently tuned to a station. In contemporary applications, IR remote controls almost universally employ a pulse width modulated code, a digital language meticulously encoded and decoded by a small computer. A command issued from a remote control, therefore, consists of a brief, precisely timed train of pulses, where the presence or absence of the carrier signal, and the varying widths of these pulses, convey the intended instruction. [^citation needed] It's all just patterns, really.

## Consumer electronics infrared protocols

It is a familiar frustration that different manufacturers of [infrared](/Infrared_communication) remote controls, in their infinite wisdom, choose to employ a diverse array of distinct protocols for transmitting their infrared commands. The [RC-5](/RC-5) [protocol](/Communications_protocol), for instance, which traces its origins back to Philips, utilizes a total of 14 bits for each individual button press, a seemingly arbitrary but functional number. This specific bit pattern is then modulated onto a [carrier frequency](/Carrier_frequency), which, predictably, can also vary across different manufacturers and established standards. In the particular case of RC-5, this carrier frequency is precisely 36&#160;kHz. Other prominent consumer infrared protocols that have carved out their niche in the market include the various iterations of SIRCS, famously employed by Sony, the RC-6, another contribution from Philips, the [Ruwido](/Ruwido) R-Step, and the NEC TC101 protocol. The sheer number of these protocols is a testament to humanity's collective inability to agree on a single, sensible standard.

## Infrared, line of sight and operating angle

Given that [infrared](/Infrared_communication) (IR) remote controls fundamentally rely on light as their medium of communication, they inherently demand a direct [line of sight](/Line_of_sight) to effectively operate the destination device. This is, of course, a rather inconvenient limitation for those who prefer to command their devices from behind an armchair or through a wall. However, like any other light source, the signal can, with a touch of physics, be reflected by mirrors, offering a rather niche workaround.

Should the necessity arise to operate equipment where a direct line of sight is simply unattainable – for instance, when controlling devices located in an adjacent room or discreetly tucked away inside a cabinet – the market, ever responsive to human demand, offers a plethora of IR extenders. Most of these ingenious solutions incorporate an IR receiver, which diligently captures the incoming IR signal. This signal is then relayed, typically via [radio waves](/Radio_wave), to a remote component, which in turn houses an IR transmitter designed to meticulously mimic the original IR control signal, effectively extending the reach of your command.

Furthermore, [infrared receivers](/Infrared_receiver) themselves tend to possess a more or less limited operating angle. This angular constraint is primarily dictated by the specific optical characteristics of the [phototransistor](/Phototransistor) employed within the receiver. However, a simple and effective method to broaden this operating angle is to strategically place a matte transparent object directly in front of the receiver, diffusing the incoming light and allowing for a slightly more forgiving aim. A small concession to our collective lack of precision.

## Radio remote control systems

