For those who find the inherent limitations of [infrared](/Infrared_communication) (IR) systems, particularly their stubborn insistence on line-of-sight, utterly intolerable, there exists the more robust and versatile realm of [radio remote control](/Radio_control) (RF remote control). This technology is deployed to command distant objects through the transmission of a diverse array of [radio signals](/Radio_signal) originating from the remote control device itself. Acting as a powerful complementary method to IR remote controls, RF systems are the preferred choice for applications such as electric [garage door](/Garage_door) or gate openers, sophisticated automatic barrier systems, the ever-vigilant burglar alarms, and complex industrial automation systems where reliability and range are paramount.

Several established standards govern RF remotes, including the ubiquitous [Bluetooth](/Bluetooth) [AVRCP](/Bluetooth_profile), the energy-efficient [Zigbee](/Zigbee) (specifically its RF4CE variant), and the home automation focused [Z-Wave](/Z-Wave). Most RF remote controls, however, often utilize their own proprietary coding schemes, transmitting anywhere from 8 to a hundred or more distinct pulses. These codes can be either fixed, a simpler and older technology, or more securely, a [Rolling code](/Rolling_code), which changes with each use to prevent unauthorized duplication. The modulation techniques employed typically include [On-off keying](/On-off_keying) (OOK) or [Frequency-shift keying](/Frequency-shift_keying) (FSK).

Furthermore, both transmitters and receivers in the RF domain can be "universal," a term that, in this context, signifies their ability to operate with a multitude of different codings. When a transmitter boasts this capability, it is commonly referred to as a universal remote control duplicator, because its primary function is to meticulously copy the signals of existing remote controls. Conversely, a receiver with universal capabilities is known as a [universal receiver](/Universal_receiver), capable of responding to signals from virtually any remote control available on the market, thus simplifying integration across diverse systems.

A typical [radio remote control system](/Radio_control) is fundamentally bifurcated into two essential components: the transmit section and the receive section. The transmit portion is further subdivided into two distinct parts: the RF remote control handset itself and a separate transmitter module. This modular design offers flexibility, allowing the transmitter module to be incorporated as a sub-component within a larger, more complex application. While the transmitter module itself is often compact, its effective utilization typically demands a detailed understanding of its intricacies. However, when combined with the user-friendly RF remote control handset, the overall system becomes significantly simpler to operate for the end-user.

The receiver component is generally one of two principal types: a super-regenerative receiver or a [superheterodyne](/Superheterodyne) receiver. The super-regenerative receiver operates on principles akin to an intermittent oscillation detection circuit, known for its simplicity and sensitivity. The [superheterodyne receiver](/Superheterodyne), on the other hand, functions with a mechanism analogous to that found in a conventional radio receiver, offering superior performance. The [superheterodyne receiver](/Superheterodyne) is widely preferred due to its inherent stability, high sensitivity, and its relatively robust anti-interference capabilities. These advantages, combined with its often compact form factor and competitive price point, make it the go-to choice for a wide range of applications requiring reliable radio remote control.

## Usage

### Industry

Remote controls are not merely confined to the trivialities of home entertainment. In the industrial sector, they play a critical role in controlling vital infrastructure such as electrical [substations](/Electrical_substation), complex [pump storage power stations](/Pumped-storage_hydroelectricity), and sophisticated [high-voltage direct current](/High-voltage_direct_current) (HVDC) plants. For these large-scale, critical systems, it is often [Power-line communication](/Power-line_communication) (PLC) systems, operating within the longwave radio range, that are employed, ensuring robust and reliable communication across vast distances and challenging environments.

### Power line remote control

A particular subset of [Power-Line communication](/Power-line_communication) involves the transmission of remote control signals directly over energized AC power lines. This ingenious, albeit somewhat antiquated, method was once a prevalent technique for remotely controlling home automation systems, long before the advent of [Wi-Fi](/Wi-Fi)-connected smart switches and the ubiquitous "Internet of Things." It was a testament to human ingenuity in making existing infrastructure serve new purposes, even if it was ultimately superseded by more elegant wireless solutions.

### Garage and gate

[Garage](/Garage) and [gate remote controls](/Remote_control_gate), affectionately dubbed "clickers" or "openers," are an incredibly common sight, particularly in countries such such as the US, Australia, and the UK, where the convenience of automated garage doors, gates, and barriers is widely embraced. These remotes are typically characterized by their remarkably simple design, often featuring just a single button, though some more versatile models may include additional buttons to control multiple gates or barriers from a single device. Such remotes can be broadly categorized into two types based on the encoder technology they employ: fixed code and [rolling code](/Rolling_code). If one discovers miniature [DIP switches](/DIP_switch) inside the remote control casing, it is almost certainly a fixed code device, representing an older, widely used technology. However, fixed codes have justifiably drawn criticism for their inherent lack of security, as their signals can be easily intercepted and duplicated. Consequently, [rolling code](/Rolling_code) technology, which generates a unique, non-repeating code for each transmission, has become increasingly prevalent in more recent installations, offering a significantly enhanced, though never truly absolute, level of security.

### Military

The application of remote control technology in the military domain has a long and rather grim history, stretching back to the late 19th century with the demonstration of remotely operated [torpedoes](/Torpedoes). These early "guided missiles" took various forms. The early 1870s, for instance, saw the emergence of remotely controlled [torpedoes](/Torpedoes) developed by [John Ericsson](/John_Ericsson) (utilizing [pneumatics](/Pneumatics)), [John Louis Lay](/John_Louis_Lay) (employing electric wire guidance), and Victor von Scheliha (also using electric wire guidance). [^34]

The [Brennan torpedo](/Brennan_torpedo), conceived by [Louis Brennan](/Louis_Brennan) in 1877, was propelled by two contra-rotating propellers. These propellers were spun by the rapid unreeling of wires from drums wound inside the [torpedo](/Torpedo). By precisely controlling the differential speed at which these wires were pulled from a shore station, the torpedo could be guided with remarkable accuracy to its intended target, earning it the distinction of being "the world's first practical guided missile." [^35] In a more visionary, if initially unappreciated, display, [Nikola Tesla](/Nikola_Tesla) publicly demonstrated a "wireless" radio-controlled [torpedo](/Torpedo) in 1898, a technology he ardently hoped to sell to the [U.S. Navy](/U.S._Navy). [^36] [^37]

[Archibald Low](/Archibald_Low) is rightfully revered as the "father of radio guidance systems" for his pioneering and crucial work on guided rockets and aircraft during the tumultuous period of the [First World War](/First_World_War). In 1917, he successfully demonstrated a remote-controlled aircraft to the [Royal Flying Corps](/Royal_Flying_Corps) and, in the same year, constructed the very first wire-guided rocket. As the head of the highly secretive [RFC](/Royal_Flying_Corps) experimental works located at [Feltham](/Feltham), A. M. Low achieved the unprecedented feat of successfully employing radio control on an aircraft, an "Aerial Target." This experimental aircraft was "piloted" from the ground by none other than the future world aerial speed record holder, [Henry Segrave](/Henry_Segrave). [^38] A critical aspect of Low's systems was the meticulous encoding of the command transmissions, a sophisticated countermeasure designed to prevent enemy intervention or jamming. [^39] By 1918, the clandestine [D.C.B. Section of the Royal Navy's Signals School in Portsmouth](/British_unmanned_aerial_vehicles_of_World_War_I), operating under the command of [Eric Robinson V.C.](/Eric_Gascoigne_Robinson), had adapted a variant of the Aerial Target's radio control system to command various types of naval vessels, including a submarine, from 'mother' aircraft, further expanding the scope of remote military operations. [^40]

The military's relentless pursuit of advanced weaponry also led to the development of several early remote control vehicles. During [World War I](/World_War_I), the [Imperial German Navy](/Imperial_German_Navy) deployed its formidable [FL-boats](/FL-boat) (Fernlenkboote) against Allied coastal shipping. These vessels were powered by [internal combustion](/Internal_combustion) engines and were remotely controlled from a shore station via several miles of wire wound on a spool within the boat itself. An aircraft would then be used to signal directional commands to the shore station. These "Explosive Motor Boats" (EMBs) carried a substantial high explosive charge in their bow and were capable of achieving speeds of thirty knots, making them a significant threat. [^41]

Later, the Soviet [Red Army](/Red_Army) employed remotely controlled [teletanks](/Teletank) during the 1930s, notably in the [Winter War](/Winter_War) against [Finland](/Finland) and during the initial stages of [World War II](/World_War_II). A teletank was controlled by radio from a dedicated control tank, maintaining a standoff distance of 500 to 1,500 meters, with the two vehicles forming a "telemechanical group." The Red Army notably fielded at least two teletank battalions at the outset of the [Great Patriotic War](/Great_Patriotic_War). Beyond tanks, the Red Army also experimented with remotely controlled cutters and various experimental remotely controlled aircraft, showcasing a broad exploration of unmanned combat systems.

In modern military usage, remote controls are inextricably linked with the constant, escalating battle of [jamming](/Radar_jamming_and_deception) and countermeasures against jamming. Jammers are strategically deployed to disable or sabotage an enemy's use of remote controls, disrupting their command and control capabilities. The operational distances for military remote controls have also expanded dramatically, now extending to intercontinental ranges, facilitated by satellite-linked systems. These are famously employed by the U.S. military for their [unmanned airplanes](/Unmanned_airplanes), or "drones," in theaters of conflict such as Afghanistan, Iraq, and Pakistan. On a far more insidious note, remote controls are also utilized by insurgents in Iraq and Afghanistan to launch attacks against coalition and government troops using roadside [improvised explosive devices](/Improvised_explosive_device). Media reports have even detailed instances of terrorists in Iraq modifying common TV remote controls to detonate bombs, a chilling demonstration of how everyday technology can be perverted for destructive ends. [^42]

### Space

In the frigid winter of 1971, the Soviet Union achieved a monumental feat, exploring the desolate surface of the Moon with the lunar vehicle [Lunokhod 1](/Lunokhod_1). This marked a historic moment, as Lunokhod 1 became the first roving, remote-controlled robot to successfully land and operate on another celestial body. Remote control technology is, perhaps unsurprisingly, an indispensable component of space travel. The Soviet [Lunokhod](/Lunokhod_programme) vehicles, for instance, were meticulously remote-controlled from ground stations on Earth. Many contemporary [space exploration rovers](/Rover_(space_exploration)) similarly rely on remote control for their operation. However, the immense distances separating these vehicles from their human operators result in significant and unavoidable time delays between the transmission of a command and the actual receipt of that command by the rover, turning even simple maneuvers into a test of patience and precise planning. Still, a robot on the moon is marginally more impressive than changing a channel.

### PC control

In a testament to the relentless convergence of technology, existing [infrared](/Infrared_communication) remote controls, once solely dedicated to televisions, can now be repurposed to control various [PC](/Personal_computer) applications. [^citation needed] Indeed, any application that thoughtfully supports shortcut keys can be commanded via these ubiquitous infrared remote controls, borrowing signals from other home devices like TVs, VCRs, or even air conditioning units. [^citation needed] This capability has found widespread adoption, [^citation needed] particularly within multimedia applications for PC-based [home theater systems](/Home_cinema), allowing for a seamless, if somewhat lazy, control experience.

For this cross-device command to function, one requires a specialized device capable of decoding the incoming IR remote control data signals, alongside a PC application designed to communicate with this decoding device, which is typically connected to the PC. This connection can be established through a traditional [serial port](/Serial_port), a more modern [USB port](/USB), or even via a motherboard's integrated [IrDA](/Infrared_Data_Association) connector. While such decoding devices are readily available commercially, they can also be ingeniously constructed at home using relatively low-cost [microcontrollers](/Microcontroller). [^citation needed] Software packages such as [LIRC](/LIRC) (Linux IR Remote control) and WinLIRC (its counterpart for Windows) have been specifically developed for the noble purpose of enabling PC control using standard TV remotes, and can also be adapted for homebrew remote control systems with minor modifications.

### Photography

Even the artistic pursuit of [photography](/Photography) has not escaped the pervasive reach of remote control technology. Remote controls are frequently employed in this field, particularly for the precise timing required in long-exposure shots, where even the slightest touch of the camera could introduce unwanted shake. Many modern [action cameras](/Action_camera), such as those from GoPro, [^43] as well as advanced [digital single-lens reflex (DSLR) cameras](/SLR_camera), including Sony's Alpha series, [^44] now incorporate sophisticated [Wi-Fi](/Wi-Fi)-based remote control systems. These wireless capabilities often allow for access and even comprehensive control of the camera's functions via [cell phones](/Cell_phone) and other mobile devices, [^45] transforming the smartphone into a versatile command center for capturing images. The act of capturing a moment, now distanced by a digital interface.

### Video games

For a considerable period, [video game consoles](/Video_game_console) largely eschewed wireless controllers, primarily due to the inherent technical difficulties of maintaining a consistent connection and the rather awkward requirement of keeping an infrared transmitter precisely aimed at the console while simultaneously attempting to play a game. Early wireless controllers that did emerge were often cumbersome, and when powered by conventional alkaline batteries, their operational lifespan was disappointingly short, demanding frequent and costly replacements. Some wireless controllers were produced by third-party manufacturers, typically opting for a more robust [radio link](/Radio_link) instead of infrared. However, even these early radio-based controllers proved notoriously inconsistent, and in many unfortunate cases, introduced noticeable transmission delays, rendering them virtually useless for any game requiring precise timing. Historical examples of these early, often flawed, attempts include the Double Player for the [NES](/Nintendo_Entertainment_System), the Master System Remote Control System, and the Wireless Dual Shot for the original [PlayStation](/PlayStation_(console)).

The distinction of creating the first official wireless game controller, manufactured by a first-party console maker, goes to the CX-42 for the [Atari 2600](/Atari_2600). The [Philips CD-i](/Philips_CD-i) 400 series also included a remote control, and the [WaveBird](/WaveBird_Wireless_Controller) was famously produced for the [GameCube](/GameCube). It wasn't until the [seventh generation](/History_of_video_game_consoles_(seventh_generation)) of gaming consoles that wireless controllers finally became the widely accepted and expected standard. Many of these modern wireless controllers, such as those accompanying the [PlayStation 3](/PlayStation_3) and the [Wii](/Wii), leverage the power of [Bluetooth](/Bluetooth) technology for their connectivity. Others, like the [Xbox 360](/Xbox_360), opted for proprietary wireless protocols, ensuring brand-specific compatibility and, perhaps, a touch of corporate lock-in.

### Standby power

A rather insidious, yet often overlooked, consequence of the pervasive convenience offered by wireless remote controls is the phenomenon of [standby power](/Standby_power) consumption. For an appliance to be capable of receiving and acting upon a command from a wireless remote, it must, by its very nature, always remain partially active, perpetually vigilant for an incoming signal. This state of constant readiness, however minimal, inevitably consumes a continuous trickle of power, even when the device appears to be "off." This seemingly insignificant drain, when multiplied across numerous devices in a household, contributes to a measurable, if often unnoticed, energy expenditure. A small price to pay for not having to stand up, or so we tell ourselves.

## Alternatives

Recognizing the potential for even greater human indolence, research has actively explored alternative methods for controlling devices, particularly television sets, that transcend the need for a physical remote. One such promising avenue is [hand-gesture recognition](/Gesture_recognition). [^47] This technology aims to interpret specific movements and gestures of the human hand as commands, allowing users to interact with their devices through a more intuitive, if occasionally theatrical, physical language. Soon, we won't even need to lift a finger, just a slightly annoyed flick of the wrist. Progress, I suppose.

